  "scenario": "In the last lesson, $\\mathrm{CaF_2}$ dissolved in **pure water**. Now dissolve it in water that is already **0.10 M in $\\mathrm{F^-}$** — a solution of sodium fluoride, $\\mathrm{NaF}$, which dissociates completely. The $\\mathrm{Na^+}$ is a spectator, but the $\\mathrm{F^-}$ is *shared* with the salt: it is a **common ion**. The very same equilibrium, $\\mathrm{CaF_2(s)} \\rightleftharpoons \\mathrm{Ca^{2+}(aq)} + 2\\,\\mathrm{F^-(aq)}$, now starts with $\\mathrm{F^-}$ already on the product side. By Le Chatelier that extra $\\mathrm{F^-}$ pushes the dissolution **backward** — so *how much less* dissolves? It is the ICE table again, with one column no longer starting at zero.",
